      "result": "\u003coutput\u003e\n{\n  \"rating\": 4,\n  \"summary\": \"The fix correctly unwraps the dict shape before crossing the `_clean_secret` sanitization boundary — NUL/CR/LF stripping is preserved on the unwrapped token. No security bypass is introduced. However, the empty-string fallback silently masks a corrupted `{\\\"mode\\\": \\\"token\\\"}`-with-no-token state as 'auth absent', and there is no type-guard on the unwrapped `token` value or assertion on `mode`.\",\n  \"findings\": [\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"suggestion\",\n      \"location\": \"src/clawrium/core/render.py:585\",\n      \"issue\": \"`auth_raw.get(\\\"token\\\", \\\"\\\")` produces an empty string when the dict is present but lacks a `token` key. `_clean_secret(\\\"\\\")` returns `\\\"\\\"`, and downstream `_render_openclaw_json` (line ~1749: `if gateway.auth: ... else: no auth key`) will then write the openclaw.json with no `gateway.auth` block — i.e. an unauthenticated gateway. While this matches the pre-existing semantics for bare-string `auth: \\\"\\\"` / `auth: null`, a dict literally shaped `{\\\"mode\\\": \\\"token\\\"}` with the token missing is a clearly-broken state, not an intentional 'auth off' signal. Silently degrading is a footgun for openclaw, whose WebSocket auth (per AGENTS.md) relies on this very bearer.\",\n      \"suggestion\": \"Raise `AgentConfigError` when `isinstance(auth_raw, dict)` and the resolved `token` is empty/missing, rather than falling through to the no-auth branch. Operators get a loud failure instead of an unauthenticated gateway.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"suggestion\",\n      \"location\": \"src/clawrium/core/render.py:585\",\n      \"issue\": \"No type validation on the unwrapped token. A `hosts.json` with `{\\\"mode\\\": \\\"token\\\", \\\"token\\\": [\\\"x\\\"]}` or `{\\\"mode\\\": \\\"token\\\", \\\"token\\\": 123}` would pass a non-str into `_clean_secret`, which calls `.replace()` and raises `AttributeError`. That's fail-closed (no bypass), but it produces the same class of confusing crash this PR is trying to fix. Also, top-level `auth: [\\\"x\\\"]` (list) sidesteps the `isinstance(..., dict)` check and reaches `_clean_secret` directly with the same AttributeError.\",\n      \"suggestion\": \"Guard with `if not isinstance(token, str): raise AgentConfigError(...)` after the unwrap, and treat any non-dict/non-str/non-None top-level shape the same way.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"suggestion\",\n      \"location\": \"src/clawrium/core/render.py:584\",\n      \"issue\": \"The `mode` field of the dict is ignored. Today the only valid mode is `token`, but uncritically extracting `auth_raw[\\\"token\\\"]` would happily forward a credential from a future shape (e.g. `{\\\"mode\\\": \\\"oauth_refresh\\\", \\\"token\\\": \\\"...\\\"}`) into the bearer slot. Low immediate risk, but the fix is the place to lock in the contract.\",\n      \"suggestion\": \"Assert `auth_raw.get(\\\"mode\\\") == \\\"token\\\"` before extracting; raise on unknown modes so a future shape change can't silently route the wrong credential type into the openclaw bearer.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"suggestion\",\n      \"location\": \"AGENTS.md (Native Dashboards / Openclaw section)\",\n      \"issue\": \"AGENTS.md explicitly documents `hosts.json.agents.\u003cname\u003e.config.gateway.auth` for openclaw as a 'flat string; the nested `.token` form only appears inside `~/.openclaw/openclaw.json` on the agent host'. This PR's comment says install.py writes the dict shape into hosts.json. Either install.py drifted or the docs are stale — the discrepancy makes the security model harder to reason about.\",\n      \"suggestion\": \"Either fix install.py to honor the documented flat-string contract (preferred — keep one canonical shape), or update AGENTS.md to reflect that both shapes are now accepted at the assembly boundary.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"suggestion\",\n      \"location\": \"tests/core/test_render.py:1300\",\n      \"issue\": \"Test coverage of the unwrap helper only exercises the happy paths (bare string, well-formed dict). The negative cases that drove findings 1 and 2 — dict missing `token`, dict with non-string `token`, top-level list — are not tested.\",\n      \"suggestion\": \"Add parametrized cases for `{}`, `{\\\"mode\\\": \\\"token\\\"}`, `{\\\"mode\\\": \\\"token\\\", \\\"token\\\": 123}`, `{\\\"mode\\\": \\\"token\\\", \\\"token\\\": [\\\"x\\\"]}`, and top-level list to lock in the intended (raise vs. accept) behavior.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"recommendations\": [\n    \"Fail loudly when the dict shape is present but `token` is missing/empty, instead of silently producing an unauthenticated gateway.\",\n    \"Add `isinstance(token, str)` and `mode == 'token'` guards on the unwrap path.\",\n    \"Reconcile the install.py shape with the AGENTS.md 'flat string' invariant — pick one canonical shape and migrate the other side, rather than carrying defensive read-both logic forever.\"\n  ],\n  \"metadata\": {\n    \"files_reviewed\": 2,\n    \"domain\": \"security-reviewer\"\n  }\n}\n\u003c/output\u003e",
